# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: advanced-spatial-index
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] In computer science, the **Bx tree** is a query that is used to update efficient B+ tree-based index structures for moving objects.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] The base structure of the Bx-tree is a B+ tree in which the internal nodes serve as a directory, each containing a pointer to its right sibling.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] In the earlier version of the Bx-tree, the leaf nodes contained the moving-object locations being indexed and corresponding index time.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] In the optimized version, each leaf node entry contains the id, velocity, single-dimensional mapping value and the latest update time of the object.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] The fanout is increased by not storing the locations of moving objects, as these can be derived from the mapping values.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] As for many other moving objects indexes, a two-dimensional moving object is modeled as a linear function as O = ((x, y), (vx, vy), t ), where (x, y) and (vx, vy) are location and velocity of the object at a given time instance *t*, i.e., the time of last update.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] The B+ tree is a structure for indexing single-dimensional data.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] In order to adopt the B+ tree as a moving object index, the Bx-tree uses a linearization technique which helps to integrate objects' location at time *t* into single dimensional value.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] Specifically, objects are first partitioned according to their update time.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] For objects within the same partition, the Bx-tree stores their locations at a given time which are estimated by linear interpolation.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] By doing so, the Bx-tree keeps a consistent view of all objects within the same partition without storing the update time of each object.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] Secondly, the space is partitioned by a grid and the location of an object is linearized within the partitions according to a space-filling curve, e.g., the Peano or Hilbert curves.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] Here index-partition is an index partition determined by the update time and xrep is the space-filling curve value of the object position at the indexed time, $\left[X\right]_{2}$ denotes the binary value of x, and “+” means concatenation.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] O’s position at the label timestamp of partition 0 is (1,5).
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] Using Z-curve with order = 3, the Z-value of O, i.e., xrep is (010011)2.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] Concatenating indexpartition and xrep, Bxvalue (00010011)2=19.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] Given a new object, its index key is computed and then the object is inserted into the Bx-tree as in the B+ tree.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] An update consists of a deletion followed by an insertion.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] An auxiliary structure is employed to keep the latest key of each index so that an object can be deleted by searching for the key.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] The indexing key is computed before affecting the tree.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] In this way, the Bx-tree directly inherits the good properties of the B+ tree and achieves efficient update performance.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] A range query retrieves all objects whose location falls within the rectangular range $q=\left(\left[qx1,qy1\right];\left[qx2;qy2\right]\right)$ at time $tq$ not prior to the current time.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] The Bx-tree uses query-window enlargement technique to answer queries.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] Since the Bx-tree stores an object's location as of sometime after its update time, the enlargement involves two cases: a location must either be brought back to an earlier time or forward to a later time.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] The main idea is to enlarge the query window so that it encloses all objects whose positions are not within query window at its label timestamp but will enter the query window at the query timestamp.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] After the enlargement, the partitions of the Bx-tree need to be traversed to find objects falling in the enlarged query window.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] In each partition, the use of a space-filling curve means that a range query in the native, two-dimensional space becomes a set of range queries in the transformed, one-dimensional space.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] To avoid excessively large query region after expansion in skewed datasets, an optimization of the query algorithm exists, which improves the query efficiency by avoiding unnecessary query enlargement.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] K nearest neighbor query is computed by iteratively performing range queries with an incrementally enlarged search region until k answers are obtained.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] Another possibility is to employ similar querying ideas in The iDistance Technique.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] The range query and K Nearest Neighbor query algorithms can be easily extended to support interval queries, continuous queries, etc.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] Since the Bx-tree is an index built on top of a B+ tree index, all operations in the Bx-tree, including the insertion, deletion and search, are the same as those in the B+ tree.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] There is no need to change the implementations of these operations.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] The only difference is to implement the procedure of deriving the indexing key as a stored procedure in an existing DBMS.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] Therefore, the Bx-tree can be easily integrated into existing DBMS without touching the kernel.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] SpADE is moving object management system built on top of a popular relational database system MySQL, which uses the Bx-tree for indexing the objects.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] In the implementation, moving object data is transformed and stored directly on MySQL, and queries are transformed into standard SQL statements which are efficiently processed in the relational engine.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] Most importantly, all these are achieved neatly and independently without infiltrating into the MySQL core.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] The Bx tree uses a grid for space partitioning while mapping two-dimensional location into one-dimensional key.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] This may introduce performance degradation to both query and update operations while dealing with skewed data.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] If grid cell is oversize, many objects are contained in a cell.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] Since objects in a cell are indistinguishable to the index, there will be some overflow nodes in the underlying B+ tree.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] The existing of overflow pages not only destroys the balancing of the tree but also increases the update cost.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] As for the queries, for the given query region, large cell incurs more false positives and increases the processing time.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] On the other hand, if the space is partitioned with finer grid, i.e. smaller cells, each cell contains few objects.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] There is hardly overflow pages so that the update cost is minimized.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] Fewer false positives are retrieved in a query.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] However, more cells are needed to be searched.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] The increase in the number of cells searched also increases the workload of a query.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] The ST2B-tree introduces a self-tuning framework for tuning the performance of the Bx-tree while dealing with data skew in space and data change with time.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] In order to deal with data skew in space, the ST2B-tree splits the entire space into regions of different object density using a set of reference points.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] Each region uses an individual grid whose cell size is determined by the object density inside of it.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] The Bx-tree have multiple partitions regarding different time intervals.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] As time elapsed, each partition grows and shrinks alternately.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] The ST2B-tree utilizes this feature to tune the index online in order to adjust the space partitioning to make itself accommodate to the data changes with time.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] In particular, as a partition shrinks to empty and starts growing, it chooses a new set of reference points and new grid for each reference point according to the latest data density.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] The tuning is based on the latest statistics collected during a given period of time, so that the way of space partitioning is supposed to fit the latest data distribution best.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/bx-tree] By this means, the ST2B-tree is expected to minimize the effect caused by data skew in space and data changes with time.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/gist] In computing, **GiST** or Generalized Search Tree, is a data structure and API that can be used to build a variety of disk-based search trees.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/gist] GiST is a generalization of the B+ tree, providing a concurrent and recoverable height-balanced search tree infrastructure without making any assumptions about the type of data being stored, or the queries being serviced.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/gist] GiST can be used to easily implement a range of well-known indexes, including B+ trees, R-trees, hB-trees, RD-trees, and many others; it also allows for easy development of specialized indexes for new data types.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/gist] It cannot be used directly to implement non-height-balanced trees such as quad trees or prefix trees (tries), though like prefix trees it does support compression, including lossy compression.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/gist] GiST can be used for any data type that can be naturally ordered into a hierarchy of supersets.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/gist] Not only is it extensible in terms of data type support and tree layout, it allows the extension writer to support any query predicates that they choose.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/gist] GiST is an example of software extensibility in the context of database systems: it allows the easy evolution of a database system to support new tree-based indexes.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/gist] It achieves this by factoring out its core system infrastructure from a narrow API that is sufficient to capture the application-specific aspects of a wide variety of index designs.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/gist] The GiST infrastructure code manages the layout of the index pages on disk, the algorithms for searching indexes and deleting from indexes, and complex transactional details such as page-level locking for high concurrency and write-ahead logging for crash recovery.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/gist] This allows authors of new tree-based indexes to focus on implementing the novel features of the new index type — for example, the way in which subsets of the data should be described for search — without becoming experts in database system internals.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/gist] Although originally designed for answering Boolean selection queries, GiST can also support nearest-neighbor search, and various forms of statistical approximation over large data sets.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/gist] The most widely used GiST implementation is in the PostgreSQL relational database; it was also implemented in the Informix Universal Server, and as a standalone library, libgist.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/gist] The PostgreSQL GiST implementation includes support for variable length keys, composite keys, concurrency control and recovery; these features are inherited by all GiST extensions.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/gist] There are several contributed modules developed using GiST and distributed with PostgreSQL.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/gist] The PostgreSQL GiST implementation provides the indexing support for the PostGIS (geographic information system) and the BioPostgres bioinformatics system.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] A **spatial database** is a general-purpose database (usually a relational database) that has been enhanced to include spatial data that represents objects defined in a geometric space, along with tools for querying and analyzing such data.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] Most spatial databases allow the representation of simple geometric objects such as points, lines and polygons.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] Some spatial databases handle more complex structures such as 3D objects, topological coverages, linear networks, and triangulated irregular networks (TINs).
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] While typical databases have developed to manage various numeric and character types of data, such databases require additional functionality to process spatial data types efficiently, and developers have often added *geometry* or *feature* data types.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] The Open Geospatial Consortium (OGC) developed the *Simple Features* specification (first released in 1997) and sets standards for adding spatial functionality to database systems.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] The *SQL/MM Spatial* ISO/IEC standard is a part of the structured query language and multimedia standard extending the Simple Features.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] The core functionality added by a spatial extension to a database is one or more *spatial datatypes*, which allow for the storage of spatial data as attribute values in a table.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] Most commonly, a single spatial value would be a geometric primitive (point, line, polygon, etc.) based on the vector data model.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] The datatypes in most spatial databases are based on the OGC Simple Features specification for representing geometric primitives.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] Some spatial databases also support the storage of raster data.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] Because all geographic locations must be specified according to a spatial reference system, spatial databases must also allow for the tracking and transformation of coordinate systems.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] In many systems, when a spatial column is defined in a table, it also includes a choice of coordinate system, chosen from a list of available systems that is stored in a lookup table.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] The second major functionality extension in a spatial database is the addition of spatial capabilities to the query language (e.g., SQL); these give the spatial database the same query, analysis, and manipulation operations that are available in traditional GIS software.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] In most relational database management systems, this functionality is implemented as a set of new functions that can be used in SQL SELECT statements.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] Some databases support only simplified or modified sets of these operations, especially in cases of NoSQL systems like MongoDB and CouchDB.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] A **spatial index** is used by a spatial database to optimize spatial queries, implementing spatial access methods.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] Database systems use indices to quickly look up values by sorting data values in a linear (e.g. alphabetical) order; however, this way of indexing data is not optimal for spatial queries in two- or three-dimensional space.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] Instead, spatial databases use a *spatial* index designed specifically for multi-dimensional ordering.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] A **spatial query** is a special type of database query supported by spatial databases, including geodatabases.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] The queries differ from non-spatial SQL queries in several important ways.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] Two of the most important are that they allow for the use of geometry data types such as points, lines and polygons and that these queries consider the spatial relationship between these geometries.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/point-access-method] The function names for queries differ across geodatabases.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] In mathematical analysis, a **space-filling curve** is a curve whose range reaches every point in a higher dimensional region, typically the unit square (or more generally an *n*-dimensional unit hypercube).
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] Because Giuseppe Peano (1858–1932) was the first to discover one, space-filling curves in the 2-dimensional plane are sometimes called *Peano curves*, but that phrase also refers to the Peano curve, the specific example of a space-filling curve found by Peano.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] The closely related **FASS curves** (FASS is an acronym for "approximately space-Filling, self-Avoiding, Simple, and Self-similar" curves) can be thought of as finite approximations of a certain type of space-filling curves.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] Intuitively, a curve in two or three (or higher) dimensions can be thought of as the path of a continuously moving point.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] In the most general form, the range of such a function may lie in an arbitrary topological space, but in the most commonly studied cases, the range will lie in a Euclidean space such as the 2-dimensional plane (a *planar curve*) or the 3-dimensional space (*space curve*).
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] Sometimes, the curve is identified with the image of the function (the set of all possible values of the function), instead of the function itself.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] It is also possible to define curves without endpoints to be a continuous function on the real line (or on the open unit interval (0, 1)).
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] In 1890, Giuseppe Peano discovered a continuous curve, now called the Peano curve, that passes through every point of the unit square.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] His purpose was to construct a continuous mapping from the unit interval onto the unit square.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] Peano was motivated by Georg Cantor's earlier counterintuitive result that the infinite number of points in a unit interval is the same cardinality as the infinite number of points in any finite-dimensional manifold, such as the unit square.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] The problem Peano solved was whether such a mapping could be continuous; i.e., a curve that fills a space.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] Peano's solution does not set up a continuous one-to-one correspondence between the unit interval and the unit square, and indeed such a correspondence does not exist (see § Properties below).
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] It was common to associate the vague notions of *thinness* and 1-dimensionality to curves; all normally encountered curves were piecewise differentiable (that is, have piecewise continuous derivatives), and such curves cannot fill up the entire unit square.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] Therefore, Peano's space-filling curve was found to be highly counterintuitive.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] From Peano's example, it was easy to deduce continuous curves whose ranges contained the *n*-dimensional hypercube (for any positive integer *n*).
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] It was also easy to extend Peano's example to continuous curves without endpoints, which filled the entire *n*-dimensional Euclidean space (where *n* is 2, 3, or any other positive integer).
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] Most well-known space-filling curves are constructed iteratively as the limit of a sequence of piecewise linear continuous curves, each one more closely approximating the space-filling limit.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] Peano's ground-breaking article contained no illustrations of his construction, which is defined in terms of ternary expansions and a mirroring operator.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] But the graphical construction was perfectly clear to him—he made an ornamental tiling showing a picture of the curve in his home in Turin.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] Peano's article also ends by observing that the technique can be obviously extended to other odd bases besides base 3.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] His choice to avoid any appeal to graphical visualization was motivated by a desire for a completely rigorous proof owing nothing to pictures.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] At that time (the beginning of the foundation of general topology), graphical arguments were still included in proofs, yet were becoming a hindrance to understanding often counterintuitive results.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] A year later, David Hilbert published in the same journal a variation of Peano's construction.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] Hilbert's article was the first to include a picture helping to visualize the construction technique, essentially the same as illustrated here.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] The analytic form of the Hilbert curve, however, is more complicated than Peano's.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] Let ${\mathcal {C}}$ denote the Cantor space $\mathbf {2} ^{\mathbb {N} }$ .
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] We start with a continuous function h from the Cantor space ${\mathcal {C}}$ onto the entire unit interval $[0,\,1]$ .
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] Since the Cantor set ${\mathcal {C}}$ is homeomorphic to its cartesian product with itself ${\mathcal {C}}\times {\mathcal {C}}$ , there is a continuous bijection g from the Cantor set onto ${\mathcal {C}}\;\times \;{\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] The composition f of H and g is a continuous function mapping the Cantor set onto the entire unit square.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] Finally, one can extend f to a continuous function F whose domain is the entire unit interval $[0,\,1]$ .
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] If a curve is not injective, then one can find two intersecting *subcurves* of the curve, each obtained by considering the images of two disjoint segments from the curve's domain (the unit line segment).
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] The two subcurves intersect if the intersection of the two images is non-empty.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] One might be tempted to think that the meaning of *curves intersecting* is that they necessarily cross each other, like the intersection point of two non-parallel lines, from one side to the other.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] However, two curves (or two subcurves of one curve) may contact one another without crossing, as, for example, a line tangent to a circle does.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] A non-self-intersecting continuous curve cannot fill the unit square because that will make the curve a homeomorphism from the unit interval onto the unit square (any continuous bijection from a compact space onto a Hausdorff space is a homeomorphism).
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] But a unit square has no cut-point, and so cannot be homeomorphic to the unit interval, in which all points except the endpoints are cut-points.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] There exist non-self-intersecting curves of nonzero area, the Osgood curves, but by Netto's theorem they are not space-filling.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] For the classic Peano and Hilbert space-filling curves, where two subcurves intersect (in the technical sense), there is self-contact without self-crossing.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] A space-filling curve can be (everywhere) self-crossing if its approximation curves are self-crossing.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] A space-filling curve's approximations can be self-avoiding, as the figures above illustrate.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] In 3 dimensions, self-avoiding approximation curves can even contain knots.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] Approximation curves remain within a bounded portion of *n*-dimensional space, but their lengths increase without bound.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] Space-filling curves are special cases of fractal curves.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] No differentiable space-filling curve can exist.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] Roughly speaking, differentiability puts a bound on how fast the curve can turn.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] Michał Morayne proved that the continuum hypothesis is equivalent to the existence of a Peano curve such that at each point of the real line at least one of its components is differentiable.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] Spaces that are the continuous image of a unit interval are sometimes called *Peano spaces*.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] In many formulations of the Hahn–Mazurkiewicz theorem, *second-countable* is replaced by *metrizable*.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] In one direction a compact Hausdorff space is a normal space and, by Urysohn's metrization theorem, second-countable then implies metrizable.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] Conversely, a compact metric space is second-countable.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] There are many natural examples of space-filling, or rather sphere-filling, curves in the theory of doubly degenerate Kleinian groups.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] For example, Cannon & Thurston (2007) showed that the circle at infinity of the universal cover of a fiber of a mapping torus of a pseudo-Anosov map is a sphere-filling curve.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/space-filling-curve] Wiener pointed out in *The Fourier Integral and Certain of its Applications* that space-filling curves could be used to reduce Lebesgue integration in higher dimensions to Lebesgue integration in one dimension.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/ub-tree] The **UB-tree**, also known as the **Universal B-Tree**, as proposed by Rudolf Bayer and Volker Markl is a balanced tree for storing and efficiently retrieving multidimensional data.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/ub-tree] Like a B+ tree, information is stored only in the leaves.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/ub-tree] Records are stored according to Z-order, also called Morton order.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/ub-tree] Z-order is calculated by bitwise interlacing of the keys.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/ub-tree] Insertion, deletion, and point query are done as with ordinary B+ trees.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/ub-tree] To perform range searches in multidimensional point data, however, an algorithm must be provided for calculating, from a point encountered in the data base, the next Z-value which is in the multidimensional search range.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/ub-tree] The original algorithm to solve this key problem was exponential with the dimensionality and thus not feasible ("GetNextZ-address").
[src:advanced-spatial-index/ub-tree] A solution to this "crucial part of the UB-tree range query" has been described later.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/ub-tree] This method has already been described in an older paper where using Z-order with search trees has first been proposed.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/x-tree] In computer science tree data structures, an **X-tree** (for *eXtended node tree*) is an index tree structure based on the R-tree used for storing data in many dimensions.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/x-tree] It appeared in 1996, and differs from R-trees (1984), R+-trees (1987) and R*-trees (1990) because it emphasizes prevention of overlap in the bounding boxes, which increasingly becomes a problem in high dimensions.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/x-tree] In cases where nodes cannot be split without preventing overlap, the node split will be deferred, resulting in **super-nodes**.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/x-tree] In extreme cases, the tree will linearize, which defends against worst-case behaviors observed in some other data structures.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/x-tree] The X-tree consists of three different types of nodes—data nodes, normal directory nodes and supernodes.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/x-tree] The data nodes of the X-tree contain rectilinear minimum bounding rectangles (MBRs) together with pointers to the actual data objects, and the directory nodes contain MBRs together with pointers to sub-MBRs.
[src:advanced-spatial-index/x-tree] Supernodes are large directory nodes of variable size(a multiple of the usual block size).
[src:advanced-spatial-index/x-tree] The basic goal of supernodes is to avoid splits in the directory that would result in an inefficient directory structure.
